               <msContents>
                  <summary>Dīvān by Mīrzā Zayn al-Dīn Khān </summary>

                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_219-item1">
                     <author key="person_f3079">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied">Mīrzā Zayn al-Dīn
                           Khān</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">میرزا زین الدین خان</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_2951">Dīvān</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_2951">دیوان</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa">قصیده در تتبع مولانا احمد ژنده فیل جامی موانقی و خواجه
                        شمس الدین محمد حافظ شیرازی</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">بعنایت بنده نوازی چاره ساز بی انباز دوازده تقطع شجره
                        آخرم</explicit>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note> A copy of the Dīvān of Mīrzā Zayn al-Dīn Khān, known by his takhalluṣ
                        'ʿIshq', in his own hand. Kerney identifies this poet as Mubtalā (also known
                        as 'ʿIshq'), but the dates do not seem credible, since Zayn al-Dīn was
                        composing as early as 1144 AH/1731 CE (see f.161b). Rubrics in this MS. show
                        that he travelled extensively throughout his life, working in locations such
                        as Jalandhar, Panjab, where he was patronised by Aḥmad Shāh Durrānī
                        (f.588b); Lucknow (f.335b), Murshidābād (f.344a) and Shāhjahānābād (f.360b),
                        where he participated in mushāʿiras; and Kolkata(f.348b). The Dīvān is
                        unusual, in the sense that the poet transcribes metres, says where and when
                        many of the poems were composed, and marks intertextual connections with the
                        works of other poets [JW 2018]. </note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
